{{Infobox building |name = Hutchinson Commons |image = Hutchinson Court.jpg |caption = Hutchinson Court, from ''The University of Chicago - An Official Guide'' - June, 1916. Hutchinson Commons is shown to the left of Mitchell Tower.|former_names = Men's Commons |highest_prev = |highest_next = |highest_start = |highest_end = |location = 1131 E 57th Street, Chicago, Illinois |architectural_style = [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic]] |status = extant |latitude = |longitude = |iso_region = US-IL |owner = The University of Chicago |coordinates_format = |coordinates_display= |building_type = Dining Hall with kitchens, assembly area |major companies = |floor_count = |start_date = {{Start date and age|1890}} |completion_date = {{Start date and age|1893}} |architectural = |top_floor = |tip = |floor_area = |elevator_count = |architect = [[Shepley, Rutan and Coolidge]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://digital-libraries.saic.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/mqc/id/22853/rec/50| title=University of Chicago - Hutchinson Hall | publisher=The The Art Institute of Chicago| accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> |references = }} '''Hutchinson Commons''' (also known as '''Hutchinson Hall''') at the [[University of Chicago]] is modeled, nearly identically, on the hall of [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], one of [[Oxford University]]'s constituent colleges. The great room (or main dining room) measures 115 feet by 40 feet, and was for many years the principal site of convocations of the university.<ref>{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=David Allen|title=The University of Chicago – an Official Guide|year=1919|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn= |pages=48}}</ref> It is located in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago's]] [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]] community and is currently used as a dining hall and lounge for university students and professors. The [[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter film series]] has used the original hall at Christ Church in each of its films, imparting a tourist interest in its American replicate.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}. The building was donated to the University by the banker, philanthropist and university trustee and treasurer [[Charles L. Hutchinson]] thru a donation of $60,000 (about $1.7 million in 2015) for the purpose.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hilliard |first=Celia |title=The Prime Mover - Charles L. Hutchinson and the Making of The Art Institute of Chicago|year=2010 |publisher=The Art Institute of Chicago |location=Chicago |issn=0069-3235 |pages=51}}</ref>
