{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox NRHP | name = Lorado Taft Midway Studios | nrhp_type = nhl | designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_date = December 1, 1993 | designated_other1_abbr = CL | designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_color = #aaccff | locmapin = Chicago#Illinois#USA | designated_nrhp_type = December 21, 1965<ref name="nhlsum">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=207&ResourceType=Building|title=Taft, Lorado, Midway Studios |accessdate=June 11, 2008|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> | image = 20070601 Lorado Taft Midway Studio (3).JPG | caption = View from northeast. | location = [[Chicago, IL]] | coordinates = {{coord|41|47|8|N|87|36|12.63|W|display=inline,title}} | area = | built = 1906 | architect = Lorado Taft, [[Pond and Pond]] | architecture = | added = October 15, 1966<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> | refnum=66000317 }}
The '''Lorado Taft Midway Studios''' consist of a converted and relocated [[barn]] that became the art studio of [[Lorado Taft]], one of the early 20th century's most important [[sculptor]]s.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/T/TaftMidway.html|title=Lorado Taft's Midway Studios|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003|accessdate=May 11, 2007}}</ref> It sits in the [[Woodlawn, Chicago|Woodlawn]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, Illinois]], and is owned by the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=nhlsum/>
In 1906, Taft moved his main studio from the [[Chicago Loop]] to a brick barn near the [[Midway Plaisance]]. Later, he connected a pair of frame barns to the main building to serve as male and female [[dormitory|dormitories]]. The structure was redesigned by the architectural firm of [[Pond and Pond]] to contain 13 studios for Taft and affiliated sculptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ead.lib.uchicago.edu/view-ead.xqy?id=ICU.SPCL.BG&q=Pond+and+Pond&c=a&sub=Architecture+--+Illinois+--+Chicago+--+History&page=#id1489898120|title=Guide to the University of Chicago Department of Building and Grounds Records: 1892-1965|publisher=University of Chicago|year=2006|work=University of Chicago Library, Series II, Subseries 3: Buildings|edition=J-R, Box 13, Folder 3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Lorado Taft: Sculptor and Citizen|author=Taft, Ada Bartlett|year=1946|publisher=Mary Taft Smith|page=28}}</ref>
The building was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] on December 21, 1965,<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref name="nrhpinv2">Blanche Higgins Schroer (April 3, 1976) {{NHLS url|id=66000317|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Lorado Taft Midway Studios}}, National Park Service and {{NHLS url|id=66000317|title=''Accompanying 10 photos, exterior and interior, from 1975 and undated''|photos=y}}</ref> and listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on October 15, 1966.<ref name="nris"/> It is one of the four [[List of Registered Historic Places in Chicago|Chicago Registered Historic Places]] from the original October 15, 1966 National Register of Historic Places list (along with [[Chicago Pile-1]], [[Hull House]] & [[Robie House]]).<ref name="nris"/> On December 1, 1993, it was named a [[Chicago Landmark]].<ref name=CL/>
Today, the building is home to the university's Department of Visual Arts and Creative Writing program, and has been renovated to be classrooms, offices, and studios for students and faculty.
