{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox presidential library | name = Barack Obama Presidential Center | logo = [[File:obamafoundation.png|300px]] | logocaption = Logo of the Obama Foundation, the non-profit organization that is overseeing the construction of the Barack Obama Presidential Center | image = | caption = | map_type = | latitude = | longitude = | construction_start_date = TBD | completion_date = Approximately 2020 | dedication_date = | rededication_date = | named_for = [[Barack Obama]] | location = [[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] | host = [[University of Chicago]] | architect = [[Tod Williams Billie Tsien Architects|Tod Williams and Billie Tsien]] and Interactive Design Architects | size = | cost_amount = | manager = David Simas, CEO<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/12/19/white-house-political-director-david-simas-joins-obama-foundation-as-ceo/|title=White House political director David Simas joins Obama Foundation as CEO|author=Eilperin, Juliet |date=December 19, 2016|work=Washington Post|accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref> | website = {{official URL}} }} The '''Barack Obama Presidential Center<ref name=foundation>{{cite web|url=http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/the-center|title=The Obama Presidential Center|work=barackobamafoundation.org}}</ref>''' is the planned [[presidential library]] of [[Barack Obama]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|44th]] [[President of the United States|President]] of the [[United States]]. The center will be hosted by the [[University of Chicago]], and will be located in [[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]] on the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. Once completed, it will become the 14th site in the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]'s presidential library system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/pages/presidential-library-faqs|title=Obama Foundation FAQs|publisher=Barack Obama Foundation}}</ref> The nonprofit '''Barack Obama Foundation''' was set up to oversee the creation of the Center and the building of its site.
==History and planning== The Barack Obama Foundation board consists of: Chairman [[Martin Nesbitt (businessman)|Marty Nesbitt]], a close friend from Chicago; J. Kevin Poorman, president and CEO of PSP Capital Partners; [[David Plouffe]]; Obama's [[half-sister]] [[Maya Soetoro-Ng]]; venture capital financier, [[John Doerr]]; [[Studio Museum in Harlem]] Director and Chief Curator, [[Thelma Golden]]; fundraiser and former White House staffer, Juliana Smoot; investment managers John Rogers, and Michael Sacks, and former [[Governor of Massachusetts]], [[Deval Patrick]].<ref>{{cite web|author=David Jackson |url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2014/01/31/barack-obama-library-foundation-chicago-hawaii-nesbitt-smoot/5086025/ |title=Obama library foundation is formed |newspaper=USA Today|date=January 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/foundation|title=About the Foundation|publisher=Barack Obama Foundation}}</ref> Barack Obama has a home in [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]].<ref name=StarAdvertiserHome>{{cite news | last = Gima | first = Craig | title = Obama: 'Hawaii is home,' but he probably won't live here | url = http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/obama-hawaii-is-home-but-he-probably-wont-live-here/ | newspaper = [[Honolulu Star-Advertiser|Star Advertiser]] | location = Honolulu | date = March 3, 2016 | accessdate = March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=ReutersHomeDC>{{cite web | title = Obamas likely to stay in DC for a few years | url = http://www.reuters.com/video/2016/03/03/obamas-likely-to-stay-in-dc-for-a-few-ye?videoId=367611877 | publisher = [[Reuters]] interview (rough cut with no reporter narration) | date = March 3, 2016 | accessdate = March 3, 2016}}</ref>{{efn|“I spent almost 30 years in Chicago. It’s where Michelle, where she grew up, where our daughters were born,” he said. “Hawaii is home to me,” the president said, but Chicago was his real home.<ref name=ReutersHomeDC/>}}
The foundation was formally established in January 2014.<ref>[http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/news/entry/supporters-establish-the-obama-foundation-to-oversee-planning-for-future-pr Supporters Establish the Obama Foundation to Oversee Planning for Future Presidential Library], Barack Obama Foundation (January 31, 2014).</ref> Several organizations, including the [[University of Chicago]], the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]], the [[University of Hawaii]], and [[Columbia University]] submitted proposals for the honor of hosting the institution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wgntv.com/2015/02/05/report-michelle-obama-to-pick-obama-library-location/|title=Michelle Obama to pick Obama library location: report=Obama Foundation Issues RFP to Four Potential Hosts of Future Presidential Library|work=WGN-TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/news/entry/obama-foundation-issues-rfp-to-four-potential-hosts-of-future-presidential/%7ctitle=%7cwork=barackobamafoundation.org|title=Obama Foundation Issues RFP to Four Potential Hosts of Future Presidential Library|publisher=Barack Obama Foundation}}</ref>
In May 2015, the Barack Obama Foundation and Chicago mayor [[Rahm Emanuel]] announced that the Foundation and the Barack Obama Presidential Center would be located in Chicago's South Side and would be built in partnership with the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name="May2015Announcement">Julie Bosman & Mitch Smith, [http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/13/us/chicago-president-obama-library.html?_r=0 Chicago Wins Bid to Host Obama Library], ''New York Times'' (May 12, 2015).</ref> The selection of [[Chicago's South Side]] has broad local support for reasons of civic pride as well as of the [[economic development]] it would bring in the form of [[tourism in Chicago|tourism]] and jobs, although the nonprofit group Friends of the Parks opposes the loss of parkland to build the library and has threatened a lawsuit to block development.<ref name="May2015Announcement"/>
A design advisory committee assisted in the selection of the architects. Members of the committee included sculptor [[Don Gummer]] (the husband of actress [[Meryl Streep]]); [[Ed Schlossberg]] of ESI Design (husband of [[Caroline Kennedy]], the [[United States Ambassador to Japan|U.S. ambassador to Japan]]); [[Fred Eychaner]], a Chicago radio station owner and Democratic financier; and ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' magazine editor [[Margaret Russell]].<ref name="ArchTech">{{cite web|first1=Kamin|last1=Blair|title=Husbands of Streep and Kennedy advising on Obama Center architect|url=http://chicagotribune.com/news/obamalibrary/ct-obama-library-architect-panel-met-20160113-story.html|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Seven [[architectural firm]]s were announced as finalists in December 2015 from an initial list of 140 applicants:<ref name="ArchTech"/> John Ronan Architects, [[David Adjaye|Adjaye Associates]], Diller Scofidio + Renfro, [[Renzo Piano]] Building Workshop, SHoP Architects, [[Snøhetta_(company)|Snøhetta]], Tod Williams Billie Tsien Architects.<ref>Lynn Sweet, [http://chicago.suntimes.com/politics/seven-firms-make-cut-to-design-obama-center-in-chicago/ Seven firms make cut to design Obama Center in Chicago], ''Chicago Sun Times'' 12/21/2015</ref>
Two firms, New York-based [[Tod Williams Billie Tsien Architects]] and Chicago-based Interactive Design Architects, were chosen in June 2016 to jointly lead the design and engineering of the center.<ref name="ChiTri30Jun16">{{cite web|title=Obamas choose New York architects to design Chicago library and museum|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/obamalibrary/ct-obama-library-architect-met-20160630-story.html|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=30 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barackobamafoundation.org/news/entry/Architect-Selection-Announcement |title=The Obama Foundation Announces Architect Selection for Future Presidential Center |publisher=The Obama Foundation |date=2016-06-30 |accessdate=2016-07-02}}</ref>
Two parks near the University of Chicago's South Side campus&mdash;[[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]] and [[Washington Park (Chicago park)|Washington Park]] were considered.<ref name="May2015Announcement"/> On July 29, 2016, the Foundation announced the selection of the Jackson Park site, across [[Stony Island Avenue]] from [[Hyde Park Academy High School]]. The park, designed by landscape architect [[Frederick Law Olmsted]], already houses the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Museum of Science and Industry]].<ref name="SkibaJackson">Katherine Skiba, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/obamalibrary/ct-obama-library-jackson-park-announced-met-20160729-story.html Obama Foundation makes it official: Presidential library will go up in Jackson Park], ''Chicago Tribune'' (June 29, 2016).</ref>
Construction of the center is expected to be completed in 2020 or 2021.<ref name="ArchTech"/> The estimated total cost is more than $500 million.<ref name="SkibaJackson"/>
